  "prompt": "What's the best way to calculate percentage off of something?",
  "response": "Calculating the percentage off of something is straightforward. Here\u2019s a step-by-step method to do it:\n\n1. **Determine the original price**: Identify the original price of the item.\n\n2. **Identify the discount percentage**: Determine the percentage that is being deducted.\n\n3. **Convert the percentage to a decimal**: Divide the percentage by 100. For example, if the discount is 20%, you would convert it to a decimal by dividing 20 by 100, which equals 0.20.\n\n4. **Multiply the original price by the decimal**: Multiply the original price by the decimal obtained from the percentage. This gives you the amount of the discount. \n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Discount Amount} = \\text{Original Price} \\times \\left(\\frac{\\text{Discount Percentage}}{100}\\right)\n   \\]\n\n5. **Subtract the discount amount from the original price**: Finally, subtract the discount amount from the original price to get the final price.\n\n   \\[\n   \\text{Final Price} = \\text{Original Price} - \\text{Discount Amount}\n   \\]\n\n### Example Calculation:\n\nLet\u2019s say the original price of an item is $50 and the discount is 20%.\n\n1. **Original price**: $50\n2. **Discount percentage**: 20%\n3. **Convert percentage to decimal**: \\( \\frac{20}{100} = 0.20 \\)\n4. **Calculate discount amount**: \\( 50 \\times 0.20 = 10 \\)\n5. **Calculate final price**: \\( 50 - 10 = 40 \\)\n\nSo, the final price after applying the 20% discount is $40.\n\n### Quick Reference Formula:\n\n\\[ \n\\text{Final Price} = \\text{Original Price} \\times \\left(1 - \\frac{\\text{Discount Percentage}}{100}\\right)\n\\]\n\nBy following these steps, you can easily calculate the percentage off of any item.",
